04086nam a22005535i 9780889206502DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20061999xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97808892065027 a10.51644/97808892065022doi  a(DE-B1597)667700  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 7aHIS0130002bisacsh04a1302151 aPearl, Jonathan L., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Crime of Crimes :bDemonology and Politics in France, 1560-1620 /cJonathan L. Pearl. 1aWaterloo, Ontario : bWilfrid Laurier University Press, c[2006] 4cÂ©1999  a1 online resource (188 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tChronology -- tIntroduction -- tEarly Modern Demonologists and Modern Historians -- tWitchcraft, Politics and Law -- tPolitics and Demonic Possession -- tThe Jesuits, Maldonat and the Development of French Demonology -- tPolitics, Morality and Demonology -- tThree Adversaries of Political Demonology -- tPierre de Lancre -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOne of the most intriguing, and disturbing, aspects of history is that most people in early modern Europe believed in the reality and dangers of witchcraft. Most historians have described the witchcraft phenomenon as one of tremendous violence. In France, dozens of books, pamphlets and tracts, depicting witchcraft as the most horrible of crimes, were published and widely distributed. In his book, The Crime of Crimes: Demonology and Politics in France, 1560-1620, however, Jonathan Pearl shows that France carried out relatively few executions for witchcraft. Through careful research he shows that a zealous Catholic faction identified the Protestant rebels as traitors and heretics in league with the devil and clamoured for the political and legal establishment to exterminate these enemies of humanity. But the courts were dominated by moderate Catholics whose political views were in sharp contrast to those of the zealots and, as a result, the demonologists failed to ignite a major witch-craze in France. Very few studies have taken such a careful and penetrating look at demonology in France. The Crime of Crimes: Demonology and Politics in France, 1560-1620 sheds new light on an important period in the history of witchcraft and will be welcomed by scholars and laypersons alike.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDemonologyxPolitical aspectsxHistoryx16th centuryxFrance. 0aDemonologyxPolitical aspectsxHistoryx17th centuryxFrance. 0aDemonologyxPolitical aspectszFrancexHistoryy16th century. 0aDemonologyxPolitical aspectszFrancexHistoryy17th century. 4aHistory. 4aReligion. 7aHISTORY / Europe / France.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978088920650240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780889206502423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780889206502/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles